--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/db/client.ts:22 ---
`getPool()` now relies on `process.env.DATABASE_SSLMODE` to control SSL behavior, but this env var isn’t validated in `core/env.ts` and isn’t documented in `.env.example`. Add it to env validation/docs (and clarify accepted values) so deployers can discover and control this behavior intentionally.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/auth/createSession.ts:29 ---
`createSession()` now stores `tokenHash`/`tokenEncrypted`, but it still persists the raw session JWT in `sessions.token`. If the goal is to avoid storing bearer tokens in plaintext, this is incomplete (DB compromise still exposes active session tokens). Consider migrating reads/writes to use `tokenHash` for lookup and avoid storing the raw token (or at least make the plaintext column nullable and stop writing to it).

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/auth/emailVerification.ts:27 ---
`createEmailVerificationToken()` inserts the raw verification token alongside `tokenHash`/`tokenEncrypted`. Verification tokens are bearer secrets; keeping the plaintext token in the database means a DB leak can be used to verify accounts. Prefer storing only a hash/encrypted token and updating verification to query by `tokenHash` instead of the raw `token` value.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/teams/inviteMember.ts:86 ---
`inviteMember()` stores invitation `token` in plaintext while also storing `tokenHash`/`tokenEncrypted`. Invitation tokens act as bearer secrets; persisting them plaintext keeps the main risk intact. Consider storing only the hash/encrypted token and updating `acceptInvitation()` to look up invitations by `tokenHash` instead of `token`.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/env.ts:17 ---
`ENCRYPTION_KEY` is marked optional in the env schema, but `encrypt()` / `blindIndex()` throw when it’s missing and several core flows now call them unconditionally. This will lead to runtime failures in environments where `ENCRYPTION_KEY` isn’t set (and `.env.example` currently leaves it blank). Make `ENCRYPTION_KEY` required (or conditionally required based on config), and consider treating an empty string as unset to avoid surprising validation failures.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/security/blindIndex.ts:38 ---
`blindIndex()` derives its HMAC key from only the *primary* value in `ENCRYPTION_KEY`. When rotating keys (newest first), the blind index for the same plaintext will change, breaking equality lookups against previously stored `*_hash` values. To support key rotation, use a separate stable HMAC key (e.g., `BLIND_INDEX_KEY`) or version the index (prefix with key id) and try all keys on lookup.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/auth/magicLink.ts:63 ---
`createMagicLink()` inserts the raw magic-link token while also storing `tokenHash`/`tokenEncrypted`. Persisting the plaintext token defeats the purpose of the new columns (DB compromise reveals valid login tokens). Prefer storing only a hash/encrypted value and querying by `tokenHash` (e.g., `blindIndex(token)`) during verification.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/auth/passwordReset.ts:36 ---
`requestPasswordReset()` now stores `tokenHash`/`tokenEncrypted` but still writes the raw reset token to the DB. Since reset tokens are bearer secrets, storing them plaintext is a significant risk if the DB is leaked. Consider persisting only the hash/encrypted token and updating `resetPassword()` to look up by `tokenHash` instead of `token`.

--- inline by @Copilot at 2026-03-24T16:15:55Z on core/auth/oauth.ts:202 ---
OAuth access/refresh tokens are still being stored in plaintext (`accessToken`, `refreshToken`) even after adding encrypted columns. Since these are high-value secrets, storing them unencrypted undermines the goal of encryption-at-rest. Prefer storing only `*_Encrypted` (and keep plaintext columns null/unused), with a migration plan to remove plaintext columns once reads are updated.
